<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peninsular Malaysia.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Lowland primary forest in open places at 27-120 m elevation.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
1. The appearance of the hypanthium with distinct calyx lobes was recognised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Nayar, MP" journalOrPublisher="The Journal of Japanese Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="45 - 52" refId="B59" refString="Nayar, MP, 1980. Notes on Asian Melastomataceae (3): New species and notes on the genus Macrolenes Naud. The Journal of Japanese Botany 55 (2): 45 - 52" title="Notes on Asian Melastomataceae (3): New species and notes on the genus Macrolenes Naud." volume="55" year="1980">Nayar (1980)</bibRefCitation>
as typical for 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Macrolenes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Macrolenes" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Macrolenes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the character of the stamens and its appendages closely resemble 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Dissochaeta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dissochaeta" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Dissochaeta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with a pair of filiform appendages on the alternipetalous stamens and not fimbriate appendages as is common in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Macrolenes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Macrolenes" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Macrolenes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bakh fil" authorityYear="1943" baseAuthorityName="Naud." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Macrolenes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Macrolenes echinulata" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="echinulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Macrolenes echinulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Naudin) Bakh. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">f.</emphasis>
which is also distributed in Peninsular Malaysia but differs in lacking paired hair cushions at the base of the leaves abaxiallyly (present in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. echinulata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="echinulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. echinulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and only has one pair of lateral appendages at alternipetalous stamens (which are fimbriate in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. echinulata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="echinulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. echinulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
2. 
<bibRefCitation author="Maxwell, JF" journalOrPublisher="Gardens' Bulletin (Singapore)" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="312 - 327" refId="B44" refString="Maxwell, JF, 1980b. Taxonomic notes on the tribe Dissochaeteae (Naudin) Triana (Melastomataceae). Gardens' Bulletin (Singapore) 33: 312 - 327" title="Taxonomic notes on the tribe Dissochaeteae (Naudin) Triana (Melastomataceae)." volume="33" year="1980 b">Maxwell (1980b)</bibRefCitation>
reduces this species to a variety of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. annulata" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the similarity in the number and shape of the stamens. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karton" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="M. P. Nayar" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Dissochaeta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dissochaeta griffithii" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="griffithii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Dissochaeta griffithii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. annulata" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its distinct triangular calyx lobes (truncate in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. annulata" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and hypanthium with dense simple eglandular bristle hairs (lacking or with scattered glandular bristle hairs in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. annulata" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="annulata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D. annulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
